d5bb421a-adcd-4eb7-8ef8-b2bbc8ef5dfa	2026-02-23 18:54:40.398067+00	Rumors	rumors-0298	Beaudoin Theatre - Siena University	Nov 13, 2025 8:00 PM | Nov 14, 2025 8:00 PM | Nov 15, 2025 8:00 PM | Nov 16, 2025 3:00 PM | Nov 20, 2025 8:00 PM | Nov 21, 2025 8:00 PM | Nov 22, 2025 8:00 PM	https://qxffhvuhovyygthdgume.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/program-assets/programs/d5bb421a-adcd-4eb7-8ef8-b2bbc8ef5dfa/poster/1771898582627-rumors-poster.jpg	<p>Welcome to live theater. There’s nothing quite like art unfolding in front of you in real time where you can experience the sweat, the mistakes, the mishaps and miracles. And welcome, too, to 1987—a world where “mobile phones” were rare and weighed over two pounds, screens weren’t yet glued to our hands, and people actually gathered in living rooms to talk.&nbsp; Or, in this case a living room in Sneden’s Landing, a burb just outside of New York City, where wild misunderstandings are about to take place.</p><p><br></p><p><i>Rumors</i> is my third production here at Siena. My first two were Frankenstein—part of Siena’s campus-wide celebration honoring the 200th anniversary of Mary Shelley’s groundbreaking novel—and <i>Doctor Faustus</i> by Christopher Marlowe. After those two heavy hitters, I longed to direct a comedy. To have the opportunity to explore the rhythm, precision, and physicality that make a farce sing has been a delight. There’s a special kind of magic that happens when not just actors, but humans of all ages, throw themselves fully into the ridiculous and the sincere at the same time. Coming to rehearsals over the past two months and playing with these wonderfully talented students has been the joy of my day.</p><p><br></p><p>I could dig deep and claim that Rumors is apropos for our time—that this play reminds us how misinformation, assumptions, and preconceived notions can distort reality and tie us into knots. And sure, that’s in there somewhere. But honestly, why bother? What Rumors truly offers is lightening-speed, goofy fun—something I believe is always timely, and always needed.</p><p><br></p><p>So please, let these actors and words do their work. May tonight be as much of a diversion and tonic for you, as this process has been for us.</p><p><br></p><p>- Tom Truss, Director</p>	<p>Neil Simon’s <i>Rumors</i> tells a winding, farcical tale of a chaotic dinner party where four New York power couples must hastily cover up a possible scandal.<span>&nbsp;</span></p><p><br></p><p>Our story takes place in May of 1987, in Sneden’s Landing, New York<span>&nbsp; </span>(modern-day Palisades), an affluent town on the Hudson known for its beautiful scenery and its rich and famous inhabitants. The 80s were a time of neon colors, new-wave ideas, exciting technologies, and pop culture icons; however on the other end of the spectrum, there was the cold professionalism of Wall Street, the HIV/AIDS epidemic, the Cold War, and moral panics.</p><p><br></p><p>Neil Simon was a major figure on Broadway from the 1960s through the 1990s, where he wrote over 30 plays. His 23rd play, <i>Rumors</i>, made its Broadway debut at the Broadhurst Theatre on November 17, 1988, and ran until 1990. Directed by Gene Saks, the production featured Christine Baranski, Ken Howard, Ron Leibman, Joyce Van Patten and Jessica Walter.<span>&nbsp;</span></p><p><br></p><p>- Nora Schuyler, Dramaturg</p>			<h3>Siena University Creative Arts Department</h3><p>Chair &amp; Professor: Scott N. Foster MFA</p><p><br></p><p>Professor: Mahmood Karimi-Hakak, Paul Konye, PhD, Tim Reno, DMA, Rebecca Taylor, JD;</p><p><br></p><p>Associate Professor: Krysta Dennis, PhD, Germaine Gatewood, MFA, Joshua Iddings, PhD;</p><p><br></p><p>Teaching Professor: Katria Foster, MFA</p><p><br></p><p>Scene Shop Supervisor and Master Carpenter: Jeff Sullivan</p><p><br></p><p>The Siena University Creative Arts Department offers an education that unites the visual arts, theater, music, broadcast media, and history through a curriculum designed for students to study, create, and respond to various forms of art and communication. Faculty actively advise students and guide them through specialized tracks within the major based on their interests and ambitions. Graduates of the Creative Arts are well prepared for future personal, academic, or professional work in the arts.</p><p><br></p><p>The goal of the Creative Arts Department is to engage students with works of the creative imagination. Courses meet this goal through three approaches:</p><p><br></p><p><span>1.</span> By developing the students’ aesthetic appreciation of the arts of the world in which they live.</p><p><br></p><p><span>2.</span> By enabling students to understand the arts as reflections of the cultural spirit of various epochs.</p><p><br></p><p><span>3.</span> By encouraging the development of students’ own creative potential and skill. The Creative Arts Department offers a Creative Arts Major, a Visual Art and Design Major, a Theatre Major with tracks in Acting, Design, and Management, a Theatre Certificate, a multimedia certificate and minor, a minor in Creative Arts, and a minor in Broadcast and Society.</p>	https://qxffhvuhovyygthdgume.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/program-assets/programs/d5bb421a-adcd-4eb7-8ef8-b2bbc8ef5dfa/sponsor/1772005031347-actf-full-page-sponsorship-accessible.docx.jpg	<p>Dean Christiane Farnan and the School of Liberal Arts Office</p><p><br></p><p>Dr. Margaret Madden, Provost, and the Office of Academic Affairs</p><p><br></p><p>President Chuck Seifert and the President’s Office</p><p><br></p><p>Creative Arts Chair Scott Foster and the Creative Arts Faculty</p><p><br></p><p>The Siena University Print Shop</p><p><br></p><p>You, our guests, especially our teachers, students, colleagues, family, and friends.</p>	<h3>Upcoming Creative Arts Events</h3><h3>DEC 5-5</h3><p><strong>Annual Festival of Lessons & Carols</strong><br>St. Mary of the Angels Chapel at 8:00PM</p><h3>DEC 8</h3><p><strong>Crea 311 Reception</strong><br>Foy Gallery at 1:30PM</p><h3>MAR 21-22</h3><p><strong>Misatango</strong><br>St. Mary of the Angels Chapel at Saturday at 7:30PM, Sunday at 2:00PM</p><h3>MAR 31</h3><p><strong>Juried Art Show Reception</strong><br>Foy Hall Gallery at 4:30PM</p><h3>APR 16-25</h3><p><strong>Dolly West's Kitchen</strong><br>Beaudoin Theatre at 8:00PM (3:00PM Matinee on Sunday)</p><h3>MAY 1-17</h3><p><strong>Capstone Exhibition</strong><br>Foy Hall Gallery</p><h3>MAY 2-3</h3><p><strong>Spring Cabaret</strong><br>Beaudoin Theatre at Saturday at 8:00PM, Sunday at 3:00PM</p>	{}	[]	{poster,director_note,dramaturgical_note,cast_bios,team_bios,acknowledgements,department_info,season_calendar}	[{"date": "2025-11-13", "time": "20:00"}, {"date": "2025-11-14", "time": "20:00"}, {"date": "2025-11-15", "time": "20:00"}, {"date": "2025-11-16", "time": "15:00"}, {"date": "2025-11-20", "time": "20:00"}, {"date": "2025-11-21", "time": "20:00"}, {"date": "2025-11-22", "time": "20:00"}]			
